<!-- MODULE 2: PRESENCE & BODY LANGUAGE -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="module2">
  <div class="section-intro">
    <span class="module-tag">Module 02 · 20 mins · Badge: The Magnetic Presence</span>
    <h2>Presence & Body Language</h2>
    <div class="meta">
      <span>💪 Power Pose</span>
      <span>👁 Eye Contact</span>
      <span>🤲 Open Gestures</span>
    </div>
  </div>
 
  <div class="module-section">
    <p class="theory-intro">On a TED stage, your body speaks before you open your mouth. Presence is not about looking confident — it is about <em>becoming</em> confident through deliberate physical choices.</p>
 
    <div class="theory-grid">
      <div class="theory-card">
        <div class="theory-icon">💪</div>
        <div>
          <h4>1. The Power Pose</h4>
          <p>Stand tall, chest open, hands on hips — for 2 minutes, privately before your talk. Research shows this lowers cortisol and increases confidence-related hormones, so you walk on stage already feeling powerful.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="theory-card">
        <div class="theory-icon">👁</div>
        <div>
          <h4>2. The Triangle of Trust</h4>
          <p>When speaking, move your eyes slowly in a triangle across the room: Left → Right → Center. This makes everyone feel included without the mechanical back-and-forth that looks like a "lighthouse."</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="theory-card">
        <div class="theory-icon">🤲</div>
        <div>
          <h4>3. Open Gestures</h4>
          <p>Keep your palms visible when you gesture. Research in nonverbal communication shows that hidden hands — behind your back or in your pockets — trigger a subtle distrust response in the human brain.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <div class="tip-highlight">
      <div class="tip-icon">🔑</div>
      <div class="tip-text"><strong>Key Insight:</strong> Your posture sends signals not only to your audience, but to your own brain. Standing in an open, expansive posture for two minutes before speaking literally changes your neurochemistry. Use the time before you walk on stage wisely.</div>
