          <h4>1. The Power of the Pause</h4>
          <p>The most impactful moments in any great talk often happen in silence. After making a key point, pause for 3 full seconds. Let the idea land. Let your audience breathe. Silence signals confidence, not weakness.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="theory-card">
        <div class="theory-icon">🎚</div>
        <div>
          <h4>2. Pitch & Pace</h4>
          <p>High pitch signals excitement or questioning. Low pitch signals authority and seriousness. A slower pace says "this matters — listen carefully." Vary all three deliberately rather than speaking in a monotone.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="theory-card">
        <div class="theory-icon">🗣</div>
        <div>
          <h4>3. Enunciation</h4>
          <p>Clear speech builds credibility. If your audience has to work hard to understand you, they stop trusting your message. Warm up your articulators before speaking — tongue twisters are the athlete's stretch for speakers.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <div class="tip-highlight">
      <div class="tip-icon">🎯</div>
      <div class="tip-text"><strong>Common Mistake:</strong> Most nervous speakers rush. They fill silence with filler words like "um," "so," "like," or "you know." Replace every filler word with a deliberate, confident pause. Your audience will not notice the gap — they will notice how composed you seem.</div>
    </div>
 
